Introduction 
Since the introduction of the education system, the world has changed drastically. Whereas the education system was once meant to help students transition into successful future professionals and become knowledgeable citizens, today‚Äôs education system does not prepare students for the realities of the modern workplace. While students may emerge from school with a diploma and knowledge of basic skills, they lack the skills required to handle the pressures of the workplace and strategies needed to succeed in an ever-changing field.

Body 
The traditional education system relies heavily on memorization and standard materials. Students must frequently memorize information and facts in order to pass topics and receive a good grade. This type of learning does not prepare them for the greater complexities of the workplace, such as an ever-changing environment, creative problem-solving, and business communication. Additionally, there is a lack of crucial economic understanding taught in the traditional system that requires students to become familiar with concepts such as budgeting, investing, taxes, entrepreneurial strategies, and credit management. These are all essential components of entering the workforce with confidence, yet are often neglected in favor of more traditional curriculum. 

Further, many schools provide little support for students with non-traditional educations or those hoping to transition between careers. Students who have been out of school for an extended period of time may find it difficult to secure a job due to outdated job application materials or an inability to navigate current recruitment methods. In these cases, students must find support from other organizations or learn relevant skills on their own initiative. This can be a very challenging task for those who are already overwhelmed by all the changes going in the world around them. 

Finally, today‚Äôs schools do not provide necessary guidance when it comes to preparing students for their expected role in society. For instance, learning the basics of professionalism, such as appropriate communication resources and dressing for success is essential but is rarely addressed in school settings. Moreover, much higher education focuses on academic research rather than practical applications that could be beneficial to future employees.

Conclusion 
Overall, today‚Äôs education system fails to provide students with all they need to navigate the complexities of today‚Äôs modern workplace. Rather than emphasizing memorization and older methodologies, today‚Äôs schools should incorporate entrepreneurial skills, more leadership opportunities, and additional resources to ensure that students are well equipped for their professional lives after school. With proper resources and knowledge in place, students will be better prepared for their professional journey ahead.

Hospitality management is a field of study and practice that necessitates a profound understanding of the various aspects of the hospitality industry, including accommodation, food and beverage operations, procurement, customer service, marketing and public relations. Hospitality managers typically use their skills and knowledge to create and maintain positive customer experiences and provide superior service, while simultaneously overseeing budgets and directing staff.

Along with an understanding of the industry, the pursuit and practice of hospitality management requires certain intangible traits such as customer-service focus, problem-solving capabilities, leadership skills and a natural desire to please customers. Hospitality management emphasizes the ability to recognize customer needs before and after the sale‚Äîand to maximize customer satisfaction through quality service.

The scope of hospitality management is wide and diverse; it encompasses leisure activities such as tourism, hospitality services like catering operations or restaurant service, and educational programs for management positions in the hospitality field. Hospitality education is valued for its practical experience requirements; studying hospitality management can often include paid internships with local restaurants or hotels. This experience provides valuable insight into the industry and instills fundamental business skills.

Unlike other specialized fields such as finance or marketing, the hospitality industry requires a set of skill sets that extend beyond those learned in traditional classroom settings. These include interpersonal dynamics, communication proficiency, an understanding of cultural differences, an ability to multi-task while maintaining attention to detail, and an acute knowledge of food safety codes and health regulations. Moreover, with the ever-changing technological advances impacting its operations, hospitality management requires a good understanding of digital marketing tools as well as processes to effectively target potential customers. 

To maintain a successful career in hospitality management often involves continuing professional education courses or regularly attending trade conferences for networking purposes. As technology continues to shape the industry, professionals must keep abreast of the latest trends and topics if they wish to stay ahead of the competition. 

As a career path that focuses on customer service and operational efficiency, hospitality management provides ample opportunities for individuals who are highly organised but also enjoy interacting with people from different backgrounds. With an expanding global market for travel and leisure services, hospitality management offers a great opportunity for individuals who are invested in delivering excellent experiences for visitors.
